  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of concealing the origin of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. Key legal elements typically include:\n\n1. Basic legal components:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Attempting to make illegal funds appear legitimate\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into \"clean\" money\n\n2. Typical legal definitions include:\n- Financial transactions designed to disguise the origin of criminal proceeds\n- Intentional actions to hide the true source of financial assets\n- Converting cash obtained from criminal activities into seemingly legal assets\n\n3. Common legal requirements:\n- Proof of intent to conceal illegal financial origins\n- Demonstrating knowledge of funds' criminal source\n- Showing deliberate attempts to disguise financial transactions\n\n4. General stages often recognized:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (complex transactions to obscure origin)\n- Integration (re-introducing funds as seemingly legitimate)\n\nThis overview reflects general legal perspectives, but specific definitions can vary by jurisdiction.",
